qas.question: What are teeth made out of?
What in human teeth enables proprioception?
What happens when you bite something you cant chew?

answers.text: our teeth send a message to our brain and we realise that it cannot be chewed, so we stop trying.

context: Teeth (singular tooth) are small whitish structures found <a0_0>in the jaws (or mouths)<a0_0/> of many vertebrates that are used <a1_0>to tear, scrape, milk and chew food<a1_0/>. Teeth are not made of bone, but rather of tissues of varying density and hardness, such as <a2_0>enamel, dentine and cementum<a2_0/>. Human teeth have <a3_0>a blood and nerve supply<a3_0/> which enables proprioception. This is the ability of sensation when chewing, for example if we were to bite into something too hard for our teeth, such as a chipped plate mixed in food, <a4_0>our teeth send a message to our brain and we realise that it cannot be chewed, so we stop trying.
